< text>
I don't know who the man managing the dutch door is, but he was very rude to me today when I showed my receipt to ask about an outgoing international shipment that I made on the prior day at this same post office. The problem was that the receipt states "Tracking unavailable to this destination country" even though I paid the additional 16 dollars for the Registered option on my First-Class Package International Service to Spain. (I presume the discrepancy is caused by the COVID-19 crisis that is present as I write this review.) Nevertheless, I also had ready on my smartphone the USPS Tracking webpage for this package. When I asked the man how I could verify the delivery of this package -- considering that I paid for the tracking service -- he said that the information is online. When I proceeded to say that I did check online but didn't see any information, he loudly interjected, "No!" as he circled the customs form number (tracking number) printed on my receipt. I then showed him on my phone the freshly loaded USPS Tracking webpage that stated, "Not Trackable - USPS Tracking¬Æ is unavailable for this product for SPAIN." He became frustrated and questioned if I had typed the tracking number correctly, and then I informed him that I actually copy-pasted it directly from the electronic USPS receipt that I had elected to receive via email, in addition to the paper receipt. He then said, "I don't know what's wrong with your system, but I see it tracking on my end." I informed him that I simply purchased the service on the previous day at the retail counter in very next room of this building, and this is the only information I received. He angrily went to the backroom for about 30 seconds and then came back with a printout of the package's status reported by Product Tracking & Reporting (a system in the USPS Tracking Intranet). I was content with these printouts and took them for my reference (after all, the recipient of my package deserves some evidence of progress in case of a query). Finally, I thanked the man and exited the post office. I don't understand why this had to be difficult; I don't believe I deserved his negative attitude when all I did was ask politely about the tracking information that was absent in my only available sources.< /text>

<UserId.>112693145551864404876</UserId.>< text>
A WARNING to anyone considering online ordering. Ordering ahead online gives you no priority in case of shortages; use the phone instead. We ordered a day ahead online for a Mother's Day brunch, only to find out when I went to pick it up that they were out of almost everything we had ordered. The problem, as explained to me, is that when you order on the phone, you're put on a priority list. When you order online, your order is put into a data base, and the store is notified about 10 minutes before the pickup time to "ensure freshness". What you aren't told is that your order is only as good as what they have in stock 10 minutes before pickup time. Today, Mother's Day, they had grossly underestimated what they would need and all bagels and virtually all souffles and pastries were gone when the time came to put together our order shortly after 9:30.<//text>

<userid>108819663088649173234</userid>< review>
Can you say yummers? I know I can after having a small size of that mango, raspberry and banana smoothie at San Diego blenders. I paid every half cent of $3.45 for this, and that price included the two extras I got. I asked for this smoothie to be topped with (as opposed to blended in with) granola and coconut. at first, I was disappointed because I had asked them to sprinkle my smoothie with pecans or walnuts; which they told me that they didn't have(perhaps they were just out of them?), but I decided to accept the granola as a topping. I was pleasantly surprised to find out that the granola topping included a really good amount of sunflower seeds, which you would think they would have mentioned -as I was looking for some type of nuts or seeds -basically something crunchable.. But whatever ...I got what I wanted. I am glad I stopped by, and I will be back. The small size filled me up, and in my opinion, 3 dollars and 45 cents is a fair amount up to pay for feeling like I've been nutritionalized and refreshed from fresh fruit and not from a from concentrate, powdery drink.*clears throat* aahem.."jambajuice"< /review>

<rate>2<//rate>< review>
I travel full-time and recently joined Avis to start using them soley for my rental needs. This past weekend I rented a car and everything was great until I returned the car tonight and checked my credit card to see I was charged double the rate I was quoted for the extra day I added to my reservation. When I called customer service to inquire about it, I was informed that prices always fluctuate so what I was told by the rep on the day I picked up the car was not necessarily accurate for a future date. I understand this was probably my fault for not asking the total when I called to request an additional day but I'm bummed the rep didn't clarify the quote and tell me to ask day of what the actual price may be. And I'm bummed the rep I talked to today didn't give me a total and confirm I still wanted the extra day. I should have asked and I didn't but now I'm paying the consequences. So make sure you always ask the reps what you're being charged. This experience didn't build trust and while I learned a valuable lesson I won't repeat, it also left me with a bad taste and I'll probably find a different car rental service for my future needs.< /review>

<review>UPDATE:  Avis contacted me and will be removing the $25.00 charge for switching drop-off locations.  They also said they would have their management look into the other issues with the replacement rental and get back with me.
ORIGINAL:  I have rented from Avis for years.  They boast a 100% smoke free fleet.  I picked up 2 cars in San Diego.  One for me and my brother-in-law.  We drove to LA and had a tire that wouldn't hold air, so we contacted Avis.  They first offered for us to drive to LAX to switch out our car.  We mapped LAX and it would take 2.5 hours round trip to do this, plus the time to switch out the car.  We were obviously on vacation and were only going to be spending 1.5 days in the LA areas anyway.  This was not a good option for us.  After calling 4 different Avis officers ourselves to try and find a replacement car in a better location than LAX, we then got back on the phone with roadside assistance.  Their best and final offer was to bring a replacement car to our hotel that night and pick up our car with the deflating tire.  We took this offer in hopes to minimize the time spent to resolve this issue and get back to our vacation.  They brought the replacement car to my hotel, and I didn't get in or drive the car that night.  The next morning I got in the car to get the AC turned on for my 4mo son and wife, and the smell of smoke was intense.  I noticed it as soon as I opened the door, before I ever got in the car or turned on the AC.  When I turned on the AC it was even worse, but with 90+ degree weather, just leaving the windows Dows wasn't an option for us with a baby.  When my wife got to the car she immediately directed to the smoke smell as well.  She got back on the phone with Avis to explain that the vehicle's smoke smell was so strong it was unreasonable to expect us to be satisfied with this car.  Their option again was to go to LAX to switch the car out.  LAX was an hour in the wrong direction.  We asked if there were any other location that we could stop at and were told no, that is the only place we could go to to get a different vehicle, if they still had one when we got there.    Their next best option was for my wife and I to pay for a tow truck to get a replacement car delivered to us, and then take the old car back.  We were faced with a decision at this point.  Completely cancel our agenda for this day of our vacation, which would also affect our agenda for the following day, since we were supposed to be driving to a new location, or just grit our teeth and bear it out.  We decided that we would just deal with it, since this was our anniversary and we wanted to make the best of our trip to the west coast.  Before the trip I called Avis to make sure our rental location would allow me to drop off at 4:30am, as we had to catch a flight.  They assured me that this was not an issue.  The night before we flew back home, I contacted Avis to make sure of what to do when dropping off the car after hours.  The rep said that my rental location didn't  offer after hours drop-offs, which is exactly the opposite of what their representative told me just a week prior.  I explained this to the rep.  He switched my brother-in-laws rental to drop off at the airport and the issue was solved.  For my rental, it would not allow him to do this, because the replacement car was registered as an LAX one-way, so his solution was to charge me $25.00 to make this change.  I'm disappointed with Avis for their poor customer service on this trip.< /review><name>Texas Hunter89</name>< pics>

<user_id>105853218368004682403<//user_id>< name>
Shanelle S<//name>
< Date>
1621210483478< /Date>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Review>
Moderate to strenuous trail to the highest spot in the Santa Monica Mountains (3133ft elevation). There‚Äôs free parking available if you input Sandstone Peak trailhead. You could also park at the Mishe Mowka trailhead but that lot was a bit smaller and had more people. There are two bathrooms available at the Sandstone trailhead. You can opt to go clockwise for a shorter but steeper ascent, or counterclockwise for a longer but more gradual ascent. The trail connects to others like the Secret Grotto and the Balanced Rock trail. Note that the latter is a trail that‚Äôs not maintained by the NPS so it‚Äôs overgrown.

The trail is rocky and to get up to the peak, you might need to strategically rock climb (in the loosest sense). Wear hiking boots, sneakers work give you good traction. There‚Äôs little shade so wear sunscreen and bring a hat. Dogs are allowed on the trail. No permits are required to hike. You‚Äôll most likely not have signal so bring a map / check the trail beforehand. Overall, the trail provides a great workout and the opportunity to enjoy some fresh air away from the crowds.</Review>

<rating>5< /rating>< text>
One of our favorite hikes in LA (Malibu). Highest point in the Santa Monica Mountains. Make sure you sign the book inside the bust. Best time is towards sunset but you will be hiking down in the dark. Be careful rocky terrain. 1.5 miles from parking lot to top. 3 miles round trip.< /text>

<Rating>5< /Rating><review>This hike was awesome. We took the more aggressive 3 mile loop because we were a little short on time. Round trip with a 20 minute stop at the top took us about 2.5 hours. It was heavy incline all the way the parking lot to the peak but doable. I had to stop a few times to catch my breath but it was worth it to take in the views. <user>115751080349885212919<//user>< name>
Vic Hanson</name>
< Date>
1604968869161</Date>
< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< text>
Sandstone Peak is the highest point in the Santa Monica Mountains and gives some good views. There are two nearby parking lots off of Yerba Buena Road, the Sandstone Peak Trailhead and the Mishe Mokwa Trailhead. The distance is similar from either one. There are a number of trails but they are fairly well marked but a map can be helpful. The Backbone Trail goes near the Sandsone Peak TH but passes right through the Mishe Mokwa TH. Two other interesting side hikes go to the Grotto (starts across the road from Sandstone TH) and Balance Rock, which is a side trail easily accessed from either TH. It is easy to make a loop hike using the other trails. The Grotto has a nice little pool hidden down among large boulders and Balance Rock is a huge rock standing on top of one on ground level. It is amazing that the earthquakes haven't toppled it!</text>

<user_name>Brad Perry< /user_name><date>1555927496293< /date>< rating>
5</rating>
< text>
Some of my friends who live in the LA area suggested this as a great afternoon hike. It's not easy but it's definitely not hard. Took about 30-40 minutes from the trailhead to the top. You could extend the hike by either adding more stops or continuing past the peak. The views we're great and I was luck enough to get to see some greenery. Also the drive to the trailhead is spectacular. Take some time and make sure to leave heading down the road towards the ocean, you won't regret it.< /text>

<user_name>Jimmy Famolare</user_name></record></dataset><record>
<user_id>115259491614644812641< /user_id>< user_name>
Evan W< /user_name>
<time>1480362354528< /time>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< Text>
My all time favorite hike in LA and surrounding counties. This is the tallest peak of the Santa Monica Mountain range, what more do I need to say? The whole loop trail is just around 6 miles total, and it is beautiful every step of the way. You start at a very tall elevation, so you get amazing views right from the start. It goes from canyon views, to a balanced rock on a cliff, to the staircase leading up to the monument, reminding you that you have reached the top. The views are spectacular in any direction that you look. On a clear day, you could see as far down as Ventura on the right, and the entire Santa Monica - Long Beach coastline. It is a challenge but no too difficult, so take anyone that hasn't experienced a hike like this before!< /Text>

<text>One of the most beautiful hikes in the Santa Monica Mountains.

Voted as the best hike in LA by the Modern Hiker.

Beautiful hike....great rock landscapes; great photo ops.

Trails can be very rocky.

Pack water & keep hydrated. =)

Peak Distance: 6-mile loop.

Hiking Time: 5 hours

Elevation Gain: 1100 feet.

Difficulty: Moderate - Strenuous

SOME OF THE KEY POINTS OF INTEREST you will SEE ALONG THE HIKE:

Inspiration Point - here there is a journal that visitors can sign
Balanced Rock
Split Rock
Climbing Walls
Tri-Peaks
Views of Los Angeles, including Catalina Island, Pacific Coast, Channel Islands (on a clear day)

Bring plenty water, snacks, comfy walking/hiking shoes, hat & sunscreen.</text>< pics>

This is the trailhead for the 6.1-mile Mishe Mokwa Trail. Start low in the sandstone-laden canyon and finish at the top of Sandstone Peak, the highest peak in the Santa Monica Mountains. Easily the most beautiful trail in the range.<//review>

<review>Hike about 1.5 mile. Take a left turn will lead you straight to the peak. Right turn will take you around the scene (~10miles).</review><pictures>None< /pictures><Response>None<//Response><gmapID>0x80e83b92592187f1:0xd4455f19e188b390</gmapID></record>
</dataset><record>
<user>114884144397845288655</user><user_name>Christopher Mejia<//user_name><Date>1375483474284</Date><rating>5< /rating>< Review>
One of the best hikes in the Santa Monica mountains and even the rest of LA. A fork about 1/2 mile in lets you pick a longer loop (approx. 6.5 miles), or a shorter out and back route (3 miles) that leads to the tallest mountain in Malibu. As you climb, you go through some scenic valleys, shaded tunnels underneath trees, and scenic overlooks offering views of the Conejo Valley.

At the top you'll find a small plaque dedicated to William Allen, a Boy Scout and namesake of the mountain (Sandstone Peak is also called Mt. Allen) and 360 degree views over Malibu, the Pacific Ocean and the Conejo Valley. On clear days you can even see all the way down to Oxnard and Ventura.

The other bonus is it's not too crowded compared to some other Malibu-area hikes, like Escondido Falls.< /Review>
